  "text": "Respiration rates, R, were measured in the dark on the apical portion of homobaric V. faba leaves while different CO 2 concentrations inside, c a,i , and outside, c a , of the leaf chamber were applied (Fig. 1) . The experiment shown in Fig. 2 started, step 1 , at low c a,i and c a (350 ll l ÿ1 and Dc= 0; Fig. 2A) ; step 2, c a,i was increased to 2000 ll l ÿ1 while c a remained low (Dc=1650 ll l ÿ1 ); step 3, both c a,i and c a were high at 2000 ll l ÿ1 (Dc=0); step 4, c a,i was lowered while c a was kept high (Dc= -1650 ll l ÿ1 ); step 5, the starting conditions were re-established with low c a,i and c a (Dc=0). This protocol was identical with that previously presented for N. tabacum [CITATION_1] . The measured NCER (negative values indicate R), at c a,i =c a =350 ll l ÿ1 and Dc=0 (steps 1 and 5) were regarded as reference data through which regression lines were drawn (solid lines in Fig. 2B, C) . When air pressure inside and outside the leaf chamber was similar ( Fig. 2B ; DP=0 kPa), measured R were significantly affected for c a,i 6 ¼c a (P=0.0002, n=5); note that for c a,i >c a in step 2 the positive values of measured NCER indicated an apparent CO 2 uptake in the dark. When a positive pressure of 2.0 kPa (Fig. 2C) was provided inside the leaf chamber, no significant influence of changes in Dc on measured R was observed (P=0.837, n=7).",
